storagegateway:DeleteGateway.Title: DeleteGateway

storagegateway:DeleteSnapshotSchedule.Description: Deletes a snapshot of a volume.
storagegateway:DeleteSnapshotSchedule.Title: DeleteSnapshotSchedule

storagegateway:DeleteTape.Description: Deletes the specified virtual tape. This operation is only supported in the tape gateway architecture.
storagegateway:DeleteTape.Title: DeleteTape

storagegateway:DeleteTapeArchive.Description: Deletes the specified virtual tape from the virtual tape shelf (VTS). This operation is only supported in the tape gateway architecture.
storagegateway:DeleteTapeArchive.Title: DeleteTapeArchive

storagegateway:DeleteVolume.Description: Deletes the specified storage volume that you previously created using the CreateCachediSCSIVolume or CreateStorediSCSIVolume API. This operation is only supported in the cached volume and stored volume architectures. For stored volume gateways, the local disk that was configured as the storage volume is not deleted. You can reuse the local disk to create another storage volume.
storagegateway:DeleteVolume.Title: DeleteVolume

storagegateway:DescribeBandwidthRateLimi.Description: Returns the bandwidth rate limits of a gateway. By default, these limits are not set, which means no bandwidth rate limiting is in effect.
storagegateway:DescribeBandwidthRateLimi.Title: DescribeBandwidthRateLimit

storagegateway:DescribeCache.Description: Returns information about the cache of a gateway. This operation is only supported in the cached volume, tape and file gateway architectures.
storagegateway:DescribeCache.Title: DescribeCache

storagegateway:DescribeCachediSCSIVolume.Description: Returns a description of the gateway volumes specified in the request. This operation is only supported in the cached volume gateway architecture.
storagegateway:DescribeCachediSCSIVolume.Title: DescribeCachediSCSIVolumes

storagegateway:DescribeChapCredentials.Description: Returns an array of Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) credentials information for a specified iSCSI target, one for each target-initiator pair.
storagegateway:DescribeChapCredentials.Title: DescribeChapCredentials

storagegateway:DescribeGatewayInformatio.Description: Returns metadata about a gateway such as its name, network interfaces, configured time zone, and the state (whether the gateway is running or not). To specify which gateway to describe, use the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the gateway in your request.
storagegateway:DescribeGatewayInformatio.Title: DescribeGatewayInformation

storagegateway:DescribeMaintenanceStartT.Description: Returns your gateway's weekly maintenance start time including the day and time of the week. Note that values are in terms of the gateway's time zone.
storagegateway:DescribeMaintenanceStartT.Title: DescribeMaintenanceStartTime

storagegateway:DescribeNFSFileShares.Description: Gets a description for one or more file shares from a file gateway. This operation is only supported in the file gateway architecture.
storagegateway:DescribeNFSFileShares.Title: DescribeNFSFileShares

storagegateway:DescribeSnapshotSchedule.Description: Describes the snapshot schedule for the specified gateway volume. The snapshot schedule information includes intervals at which snapshots are automatically initiated on the volume. This operation is only supported in the cached volume and stored volume architectures.
storagegateway:DescribeSnapshotSchedule.Title: DescribeSnapshotSchedule

storagegateway:DescribeStorediSCSIVolume.Description: Returns the description of the gateway volumes specified in the request. The list of gateway volumes in the request must be from one gateway. In the response Amazon Storage Gateway returns volume information sorted by volume ARNs. This operation is only supported in stored volume gateway architecture.
storagegateway:DescribeStorediSCSIVolume.Title: DescribeStorediSCSIVolumes

storagegateway:DescribeTapeArchives.Description: Returns a description of specified virtual tapes in the virtual tape shelf (VTS). This operation is only supported in the tape gateway architecture.
storagegateway:DescribeTapeArchives.Title: DescribeTapeArchives

storagegateway:DescribeTapeRecoveryPoint.Description: Returns a list of virtual tape recovery points that are available for the specified tape gateway.
storagegateway:DescribeTapeRecoveryPoint.Title: DescribeTapeRecoveryPoints

storagegateway:DescribeTapes.Description: Returns a description of the specified Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of virtual tapes. If a TapeARN is not specified, returns a description of all virtual tapes associated with the specified gateway. This operation is only supported in the tape gateway architecture.
storagegateway:DescribeTapes.Title: DescribeTapes

storagegateway:DescribeUploadBuffer.Description: Returns information about the upload buffer of a gateway. This operation is supported for the stored volume, cached volume and tape gateway architectures.
storagegateway:DescribeUploadBuffer.Title: DescribeUploadBuffer

storagegateway:DescribeVTLDevices.Description: Returns a description of virtual tape library (VTL) devices for the specified tape gateway. In the response, AWS Storage Gateway returns VTL device information.
storagegateway:DescribeVTLDevices.Title: DescribeVTLDevices

storagegateway:DescribeWorkingStorage.Description: Returns information about the working storage of a gateway. This operation is only supported in the stored volumes gateway architecture. This operation is deprecated in cached volumes API version (20120630). Use DescribeUploadBuffer instead.
storagegateway:DescribeWorkingStorage.Title: DescribeWorkingStorage

storagegateway:DisableGateway.Description: Disables a tape gateway when the gateway is no longer functioning. For example, if your gateway VM is damaged, you can disable the gateway so you can recover virtual tapes.
storagegateway:DisableGateway.Title: DisableGateway

storagegateway:ListFileShares.Description: Gets a list of the file shares for a specific file gateway, or the list of file shares that belong to the calling user account. This operation is only supported in the file gateway architecture.
storagegateway:ListFileShares.Title: ListFileShares

storagegateway:ListGateways.Description: Lists gateways owned by an AWS account in a region specified in the request. The returned list is ordered by gateway Amazon Resource Name (ARN).
storagegateway:ListGateways.Title: ListGateways

storagegateway:ListLocalDisks.Description: Returns a list of the gateway's local disks. To specify which gateway to describe, you use the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the gateway in the body of the request.
storagegateway:ListLocalDisks.Title: ListLocalDisks

storagegateway:ListTagsForResource.Description: Lists the tags that have been added to the specified resource. This operation is only supported in the cached volume, stored volume and tape gateway architecture.
storagegateway:ListTagsForResource.Title: ListTagsForResource

storagegateway:ListTapes.Description: Lists virtual tapes in your virtual tape library (VTL) and your virtual tape shelf (VTS). You specify the tapes to list by specifying one or more tape Amazon Resource Names (ARNs). If you don't specify a tape ARN, the operation lists all virtual tapes in both your VTL and VTS.
storagegateway:ListTapes.Title: ListTapes

storagegateway:ListVolumeRecoveryPoints.Description: Lists the recovery points for a specified gateway. This operation is only supported in the cached volume gateway architecture.
storagegateway:ListVolumeRecoveryPoints.Title: ListVolumeRecoveryPoints

storagegateway:ListVolumes.Description: Lists the iSCSI stored volumes of a gateway. Results are sorted by volume ARN. The response includes only the volume ARNs. If you want additional volume information, use the DescribeStorediSCSIVolumes or the DescribeCachediSCSIVolumes API.
storagegateway:ListVolumes.Title: ListVolumes

storagegateway:RefreshCache.Description: Refreshes the cache for the specified file share. This operation finds objects in the Amazon S3 bucket that were added, removed or replaced since the gateway last listed the bucket's contents and cached the results. This operation is only supported in the file gateway architecture.
storagegateway:RefreshCache.Title: RefreshCache

storagegateway:RetrieveTapeArchive.Description: Retrieves an archived virtual tape from the virtual tape shelf (VTS) to a tape gateway. Virtual tapes archived in the VTS are not associated with any gateway. However after a tape is retrieved, it is associated with a gateway, even though it is also listed in the VTS, that is, archive. This operation is only supported in the tape gateway architecture.
storagegateway:RetrieveTapeArchive.Title: RetrieveTapeArchive

storagegateway:RetrieveTapeRecoveryPoint.Description: Retrieves the recovery point for the specified virtual tape. This operation is only supported in the tape gateway architecture.
storagegateway:RetrieveTapeRecoveryPoint.Title: RetrieveTapeRecoveryPoint

storagegateway:SetLocalConsolePassword.Description: Sets the password for your VM local console. When you log in to the local console for the first time, you log in to the VM with the default credentials. We recommend that you set a new password. You don't need to know the default password to set a new password.
storagegateway:SetLocalConsolePassword.Title: SetLocalConsolePassword

storagegateway:ShutdownGateway.Description: Shuts down a gateway. To specify which gateway to shut down, use the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the gateway in the body of your request.
storagegateway:ShutdownGateway.Title: ShutdownGateway

storagegateway:StartGateway.Description: Starts a gateway that you previously shut down (see ShutdownGateway). After the gateway starts, you can then make other API calls, your applications can read from or write to the gateway's storage volumes and you will be able to take snapshot backups.
storagegateway:StartGateway.Title: StartGateway

storagegateway:UpdateBandwidthRateLimit.Description: Updates the bandwidth rate limits of a gateway. You can update both the upload and download bandwidth rate limit or specify only one of the two. If you don't set a bandwidth rate limit, the existing rate limit remains.
storagegateway:UpdateBandwidthRateLimit.Title: UpdateBandwidthRateLimit

storagegateway:UpdateChapCredentials.Description: Updates the Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol (CHAP) credentials for a specified iSCSI target. By default, a gateway does not have CHAP enabled; however, for added security, you might use it.
storagegateway:UpdateChapCredentials.Title: UpdateChapCredentials

storagegateway:UpdateGatewayInformation.Description: Updates a gateway's metadata, which includes the gateway's name and time zone. To specify which gateway to update, use the Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the gateway in your request.
storagegateway:UpdateGatewayInformation.Title: UpdateGatewayInformation

storagegateway:UpdateGatewaySoftwareNow.Description: Updates the gateway virtual machine (VM) software. The request immediately triggers the software update.
storagegateway:UpdateGatewaySoftwareNow.Title: UpdateGatewaySoftwareNow

storagegateway:UpdateMaintenanceStartTim.Description: Updates a gateway's weekly maintenance start time information, including day and time of the week. The maintenance time is the time in your gateway's time zone.
storagegateway:UpdateMaintenanceStartTim.Title: UpdateMaintenanceStartTime

storagegateway:UpdateNFSFileShare.Description: Updates a file share. This operation is only supported in the file gateway architecture.
storagegateway:UpdateNFSFileShare.Title: UpdateNFSFileShare

storagegateway:UpdateSnapshotSchedule.Description: Updates a snapshot schedule configured for a gateway volume. This operation is only supported in the cached volume and stored volume gateway architectures.
storagegateway:UpdateSnapshotSchedule.Title: UpdateSnapshotSchedule

sts:AssumeRole.Description: Returns a set of temporary security credentials (consisting of an access key ID, a secret access key, and a security token) that you can use to access AWS resources that you might not normally have access to. Typically, you use AssumeRole for cross-account access or federation. For a comparison of AssumeRole with the other APIs that produce temporary credentials, see Requesting Temporary Security Credentials and Comparing the AWS STS APIs in the IAM User Guide.
sts:AssumeRole.Title: AssumeRole

sts:AssumeRoleWithSAML.Description: Returns a set of temporary security credentials for users who have been authenticated via a SAML authentication response. This operation provides a mechanism for tying an enterprise identity store or directory to role-based AWS access without user-specific credentials or configuration. For a comparison of AssumeRoleWithSAML with the other APIs that produce temporary credentials, see Requesting Temporary Security Credentials and Comparing the AWS STS APIs in the IAM User Guide.
sts:AssumeRoleWithSAML.Title: AssumeRoleWithSAML

sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity.Description: Returns a set of temporary security credentials for users who have been authenticated in a mobile or web application with a web identity provider, such as Amazon Cognito, Login with Amazon, Facebook, Google, or any OpenID Connect-compatible identity provider.
sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity.Title: AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity

sts:DecodeAuthorizationMessage.Description: Decodes additional information about the authorization status of a request from an encoded message returned in response to an AWS request.
sts:DecodeAuthorizationMessage.Title: DecodeAuthorizationMessage

sts:GetFederationToken.Description: Returns a set of temporary security credentials (consisting of an access key ID, a secret access key, and a security token) for a federated user. A typical use is in a proxy application that gets temporary security credentials on behalf of distributed applications inside a corporate network. Because you must call the GetFederationToken action using the long-term security credentials of an IAM user, this call is appropriate in contexts where those credentials can be safely stored, usually in a server-based application. For a comparison of GetFederationToken with the other APIs that produce temporary credentials, see Requesting Temporary Security Credentials and Comparing the AWS STS APIs in the IAM User Guide.
sts:GetFederationToken.Title: GetFederationToken

sts:GetSessionToken.Description: Returns a set of temporary credentials for an AWS account or IAM user. The credentials consist of an access key ID, a secret access key, and a security token. Typically, you use GetSessionToken if you want to use MFA to protect programmatic calls to specific AWS APIs like Amazon EC2 StopInstances. MFA-enabled IAM users would need to call GetSessionToken and submit an MFA code that is associated with their MFA device. Using the temporary security credentials that are returned from the call, IAM users can then make programmatic calls to APIs that require MFA authentication. If you do not supply a correct MFA code, then the API returns an access denied error. For a comparison of GetSessionToken with the other APIs that produce temporary credentials, see Requesting Temporary Security Credentials and Comparing the AWS STS APIs in the IAM User Guide.
sts:GetSessionToken.Title: GetSessionToken

swf:CountClosedWorkflowExecutions.Description: Returns the number of closed workflow executions within the given domain that meet the specified filtering criteria.
swf:CountClosedWorkflowExecutions.Title: CountClosedWorkflowExecutions

swf:CountOpenWorkflowExecutions.Description: Returns the number of open workflow executions within the given domain that meet the specified filtering criteria.
swf:CountOpenWorkflowExecutions.Title: CountOpenWorkflowExecutions

swf:CountPendingActivityTasks.Description: Returns the estimated number of activity tasks in the specified task list. The count returned is an approximation and isn't guaranteed to be exact. If you specify a task list that no activity task was ever scheduled in then 0 is returned.
swf:CountPendingActivityTasks.Title: CountPendingActivityTasks

swf:CountPendingDecisionTasks.Description: Returns the estimated number of decision tasks in the specified task list. The count returned is an approximation and isn't guaranteed to be exact. If you specify a task list that no decision task was ever scheduled in then 0 is returned.
swf:CountPendingDecisionTasks.Title: CountPendingDecisionTasks

swf:DeprecateActivityType.Description: Deprecates the specified activity type. After an activity type has been deprecated, you cannot create new tasks of that activity type. Tasks of this type that were scheduled before the type was deprecated continue to run.
swf:DeprecateActivityType.Title: DeprecateActivityType

swf:DeprecateDomain.Description: Deprecates the specified domain. After a domain has been deprecated it cannot be used to create new workflow executions or register new types. However, you can still use visibility actions on this domain. Deprecating a domain also deprecates all activity and workflow types registered in the domain. Executions that were started before the domain was deprecated continues to run.
swf:DeprecateDomain.Title: DeprecateDomain

swf:DeprecateWorkflowType.Description: Deprecates the specified workflow type. After a workflow type has been deprecated, you cannot create new executions of that type. Executions that were started before the type was deprecated continues to run. A deprecated workflow type may still be used when calling visibility actions.
swf:DeprecateWorkflowType.Title: DeprecateWorkflowType

swf:DescribeActivityType.Description: Returns information about the specified activity type. This includes configuration settings provided when the type was registered and other general information about the type.
swf:DescribeActivityType.Title: DescribeActivityType

swf:DescribeDomain.Description: Returns information about the specified domain, including description and status.
swf:DescribeDomain.Title: DescribeDomain

swf:DescribeWorkflowExecution.Description: Returns information about the specified workflow execution including its type and some statistics.
swf:DescribeWorkflowExecution.Title: DescribeWorkflowExecution

swf:DescribeWorkflowType.Description: Returns information about the specified workflow type. This includes configuration settings specified when the type was registered and other information such as creation date, current status, etc.
swf:DescribeWorkflowType.Title: DescribeWorkflowType

swf:GetWorkflowExecutionHistory.Description: Returns the history of the specified workflow execution. The results may be split into multiple pages. To retrieve subsequent pages, make the call again using the nextPageToken returned by the initial call.
swf:GetWorkflowExecutionHistory.Title: GetWorkflowExecutionHistory

swf:ListActivityTypes.Description: Returns information about all activities registered in the specified domain that match the specified name and registration status. The result includes information like creation date, current status of the activity, etc. The results may be split into multiple pages. To retrieve subsequent pages, make the call again using the nextPageToken returned by the initial call.
swf:ListActivityTypes.Title: ListActivityTypes

swf:ListClosedWorkflowExecutions.Description: Returns a list of closed workflow executions in the specified domain that meet the filtering criteria. The results may be split into multiple pages. To retrieve subsequent pages, make the call again using the nextPageToken returned by the initial call.
swf:ListClosedWorkflowExecutions.Title: ListClosedWorkflowExecutions

swf:ListDomains.Description: Returns the list of domains registered in the account. The results may be split into multiple pages. To retrieve subsequent pages, make the call again using the nextPageToken returned by the initial call.
swf:ListDomains.Title: ListDomains

swf:ListOpenWorkflowExecutions.Description: Returns a list of open workflow executions in the specified domain that meet the filtering criteria. The results may be split into multiple pages. To retrieve subsequent pages, make the call again using the nextPageToken returned by the initial call.
swf:ListOpenWorkflowExecutions.Title: ListOpenWorkflowExecutions

swf:ListWorkflowTypes.Description: Returns information about workflow types in the specified domain. The results may be split into multiple pages that can be retrieved by making the call repeatedly.
swf:ListWorkflowTypes.Title: ListWorkflowTypes

swf:PollForActivityTask.Description: Used by workers to get an ActivityTask from the specified activity taskList. This initiates a long poll, where the service holds the HTTP connection open and responds as soon as a task becomes available. The maximum time the service holds on to the request before responding is 60 seconds. If no task is available within 60 seconds, the poll returns an empty result. An empty result, in this context, means that an ActivityTask is returned, but that the value of taskToken is an empty string. If a task is returned, the worker should use its type to identify and process it correctly.
swf:PollForActivityTask.Title: PollForActivityTask

swf:PollForDecisionTask.Description: Used by deciders to get a DecisionTask from the specified decision taskList. A decision task may be returned for any open workflow execution that is using the specified task list. The task includes a paginated view of the history of the workflow execution. The decider should use the workflow type and the history to determine how to properly handle the task.
swf:PollForDecisionTask.Title: PollForDecisionTask

swf:RecordActivityTaskHeartbeat.Description: Used by activity workers to report to the service that the ActivityTask represented by the specified taskToken is still making progress. The worker can also specify details of the progress, for example percent complete, using the details parameter. This action can also be used by the worker as a mechanism to check if cancellation is being requested for the activity task. If a cancellation is being attempted for the specified task, then the boolean cancelRequested flag returned by the service is set to true.
swf:RecordActivityTaskHeartbeat.Title: RecordActivityTaskHeartbeat

swf:RegisterActivityType.Description: Registers a new activity type along with its configuration settings in the specified domain.
swf:RegisterActivityType.Title: RegisterActivityType

swf:RegisterWorkflowType.Description: Registers a new workflow type and its configuration settings in the specified domain.
swf:RegisterWorkflowType.Title: RegisterWorkflowType

swf:RequestCancelWorkflowExecution.Description: Records a WorkflowExecutionCancelRequested event in the currently running workflow execution identified by the given domain, workflowId, and runId. This logically requests the cancellation of the workflow execution as a whole. It is up to the decider to take appropriate actions when it receives an execution history with this event.
swf:RequestCancelWorkflowExecution.Title: RequestCancelWorkflowExecution

swf:RespondActivityTaskCanceled.Description: Used by workers to tell the service that the ActivityTask identified by the taskToken was successfully canceled. Additional details can be provided using the details argument.
swf:RespondActivityTaskCanceled.Title: RespondActivityTaskCanceled

swf:RespondActivityTaskCompleted.Description: Used by workers to tell the service that the ActivityTask identified by the taskToken completed successfully with a result (if provided). The result appears in the ActivityTaskCompleted event in the workflow history.
swf:RespondActivityTaskCompleted.Title: RespondActivityTaskCompleted

swf:RespondActivityTaskFailed.Description: Used by workers to tell the service that the ActivityTask identified by the taskToken has failed with reason (if specified). The reason and details appear in the ActivityTaskFailed event added to the workflow history.
swf:RespondActivityTaskFailed.Title: RespondActivityTaskFailed

swf:RespondDecisionTaskCompleted.Description: Used by deciders to tell the service that the DecisionTask identified by the taskToken has successfully completed. The decisions argument specifies the list of decisions made while processing the task.
swf:RespondDecisionTaskCompleted.Title: RespondDecisionTaskCompleted

swf:SignalWorkflowExecution.Description: Records a WorkflowExecutionSignaled event in the workflow execution history and creates a decision task for the workflow execution identified by the given domain, workflowId and runId. The event is recorded with the specified user defined signalName and input (if provided).
swf:SignalWorkflowExecution.Title: SignalWorkflowExecution

swf:StartWorkflowExecution.Description: Starts an execution of the workflow type in the specified domain using the provided workflowId and input data.
swf:StartWorkflowExecution.Title: StartWorkflowExecution

swf:TerminateWorkflowExecution.Description: Records a WorkflowExecutionTerminated event and forces closure of the workflow execution identified by the given domain, runId, and workflowId. The child policy, registered with the workflow type or specified when starting this execution, is applied to any open child workflow executions of this workflow execution.
swf:TerminateWorkflowExecution.Title: TerminateWorkflowExecution

tag:GetResources.Description: Returns all the tagged resources that are associated with the specified tags (keys and values) located in the specified region for the AWS account. The tags and the resource types that you specify in the request are known as filters. The response includes all tags that are associated with the requested resources. If no filter is provided, this action returns a paginated resource list with the associated tags.
tag:GetResources.Title: GetResources

tag:GetTagKeys.Description: Returns all tag keys in the specified region for the AWS account.
tag:GetTagKeys.Title: GetTagKeys

tag:GetTagValues.Description: Returns all tag values for the specified key in the specified region for the AWS account.
tag:GetTagValues.Title: GetTagValues

tag:TagResources.Description: Applies one or more tags to the specified resources. Note the following:
tag:TagResources.Title: TagResources

tag:UntagResources.Description: Removes the specified tags from the specified resources. When you specify a tag key, the action removes both that key and its associated value. The operation succeeds even if you attempt to remove tags from a resource that were already removed. Note the following:
tag:UntagResources.Title: UntagResources

waf:CreateByteMatchSet.Description: Creates a ByteMatchSet. You then use UpdateByteMatchSet to identify the part of a web request that you want AWS WAF to inspect, such as the values of the User-Agent header or the query string. For example, you can create a ByteMatchSet that matches any requests with User-Agent headers that contain the string BadBot. You can then configure AWS WAF to reject those requests.
waf:CreateByteMatchSet.Title: CreateByteMatchSet

waf:CreateIPSet.Description: Creates an IPSet, which you use to specify which web requests you want to allow or block based on the IP addresses that the requests originate from. For example, if you're receiving a lot of requests from one or more individual IP addresses or one or more ranges of IP addresses and you want to block the requests, you can create an IPSet that contains those IP addresses and then configure AWS WAF to block the requests.
waf:CreateIPSet.Title: CreateIPSet

waf:CreateRateBasedRule.Description: Creates a RateBasedRule. The RateBasedRule contains a RateLimit, which specifies the maximum number of requests that AWS WAF allows from a specified IP address in a five-minute period. The RateBasedRule also contains the IPSet objects, ByteMatchSet objects, and other predicates that identify the requests that you want to count or block if these requests exceed the RateLimit.
waf:CreateRateBasedRule.Title: CreateRateBasedRule

waf:CreateRule.Description: Creates a Rule, which contains the IPSet objects, ByteMatchSet objects, and other predicates that identify the requests that you want to block. If you add more than one predicate to a Rule, a request must match all of the specifications to be allowed or blocked. For example, suppose you add the following to a Rule:
waf:CreateRule.Title: CreateRule

waf:CreateSizeConstraintSet.Description: Creates a SizeConstraintSet. You then use UpdateSizeConstraintSet to identify the part of a web request that you want AWS WAF to check for length, such as the length of the User-Agent header or the length of the query string. For example, you can create a SizeConstraintSet that matches any requests that have a query string that is longer than 100 bytes. You can then configure AWS WAF to reject those requests.
waf:CreateSizeConstraintSet.Title: CreateSizeConstraintSet

waf:CreateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Creates a SqlInjectionMatchSet, which you use to allow, block, or count requests that contain snippets of SQL code in a specified part of web requests. AWS WAF searches for character sequences that are likely to be malicious strings.
waf:CreateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: CreateSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf:CreateWebACL.Description: Creates a WebACL, which contains the Rules that identify the CloudFront web requests that you want to allow, block, or count. AWS WAF evaluates Rules in order based on the value of Priority for each Rule.
waf:CreateWebACL.Title: CreateWebACL

waf:CreateXssMatchSet.Description: Creates an XssMatchSet, which you use to allow, block, or count requests that contain cross-site scripting attacks in the specified part of web requests. AWS WAF searches for character sequences that are likely to be malicious strings.
waf:CreateXssMatchSet.Title: CreateXssMatchSet

waf:DeleteByteMatchSet.Description: Permanently deletes a ByteMatchSet. You can't delete a ByteMatchSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still includes any ByteMatchTuple objects (any filters).
waf:DeleteByteMatchSet.Title: DeleteByteMatchSet

waf:DeleteIPSet.Description: Permanently deletes an IPSet. You can't delete an IPSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still includes any IP addresses.
waf:DeleteIPSet.Title: DeleteIPSet

waf:DeleteRateBasedRule.Description: Permanently deletes a RateBasedRule. You can't delete a rule if it's still used in any WebACL objects or if it still includes any predicates, such as ByteMatchSet objects.
waf:DeleteRateBasedRule.Title: DeleteRateBasedRule

waf:DeleteRule.Description: Permanently deletes a Rule. You can't delete a Rule if it's still used in any WebACL objects or if it still includes any predicates, such as ByteMatchSet objects.
waf:DeleteRule.Title: DeleteRule

waf:DeleteSizeConstraintSet.Description: Permanently deletes a SizeConstraintSet. You can't delete a SizeConstraintSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still includes any SizeConstraint objects (any filters).
waf:DeleteSizeConstraintSet.Title: DeleteSizeConstraintSet

waf:DeleteSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Permanently deletes a SqlInjectionMatchSet. You can't delete a SqlInjectionMatchSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still contains any SqlInjectionMatchTuple objects.
waf:DeleteSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: DeleteSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf:DeleteWebACL.Description: Permanently deletes a WebACL. You can't delete a WebACL if it still contains any Rules.
waf:DeleteWebACL.Title: DeleteWebACL

waf:DeleteXssMatchSet.Description: Permanently deletes an XssMatchSet. You can't delete an XssMatchSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still contains any XssMatchTuple objects.
waf:DeleteXssMatchSet.Title: DeleteXssMatchSet

waf:GetByteMatchSet.Description: Returns the ByteMatchSet specified by ByteMatchSetId.
waf:GetByteMatchSet.Title: GetByteMatchSet

waf:GetChangeToken.Description: When you want to create, update, or delete AWS WAF objects, get a change token and include the change token in the create, update, or delete request. Change tokens ensure that your application doesn't submit conflicting requests to AWS WAF.
waf:GetChangeToken.Title: GetChangeToken

waf:GetChangeTokenStatus.Description: Returns the status of a ChangeToken that you got by calling GetChangeToken. ChangeTokenStatus is one of the following values:
waf:GetChangeTokenStatus.Title: GetChangeTokenStatus

waf:GetIPSet.Description: Returns the IPSet that is specified by IPSetId.
waf:GetIPSet.Title: GetIPSet

waf:GetRateBasedRule.Description: Returns the RateBasedRule that is specified by the RuleId that you included in the GetRateBasedRule request.
waf:GetRateBasedRule.Title: GetRateBasedRule

waf:GetRateBasedRuleManagedKeys.Description: Returns an array of IP addresses currently being blocked by the RateBasedRule that is specified by the RuleId. The maximum number of managed keys that will be blocked is 10,000. If more than 10,000 addresses exceed the rate limit, the 10,000 addresses with the highest rates will be blocked.
waf:GetRateBasedRuleManagedKeys.Title: GetRateBasedRuleManagedKeys

waf:GetRule.Description: Returns the Rule that is specified by the RuleId that you included in the GetRule request.
waf:GetRule.Title: GetRule

waf:GetSampledRequests.Description: Gets detailed information about a specified number of requests--a sample--that AWS WAF randomly selects from among the first 5,000 requests that your AWS resource received during a time range that you choose. You can specify a sample size of up to 500 requests, and you can specify any time range in the previous three hours.
waf:GetSampledRequests.Title: GetSampledRequests

waf:GetSizeConstraintSet.Description: Returns the SizeConstraintSet specified by SizeConstraintSetId.
waf:GetSizeConstraintSet.Title: GetSizeConstraintSet

waf:GetSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Returns the SqlInjectionMatchSet that is specified by SqlInjectionMatchSetId.
waf:GetSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: GetSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf:GetWebACL.Description: Returns the WebACL that is specified by WebACLId.
waf:GetWebACL.Title: GetWebACL

waf:GetXssMatchSet.Description: Returns the XssMatchSet that is specified by XssMatchSetId.
waf:GetXssMatchSet.Title: GetXssMatchSet

waf:ListByteMatchSets.Description: Returns an array of ByteMatchSetSummary objects.
waf:ListByteMatchSets.Title: ListByteMatchSets

waf:ListIPSets.Description: Returns an array of IPSetSummary objects in the response.
waf:ListIPSets.Title: ListIPSets

waf:ListRules.Description: Returns an array of RuleSummary objects.
waf:ListRules.Title: ListRules

waf:ListSizeConstraintSets.Description: Returns an array of SizeConstraintSetSummary objects.
waf:ListSizeConstraintSets.Title: ListSizeConstraintSets

waf:ListSqlInjectionMatchSets.Description: Returns an array of SqlInjectionMatchSet objects.
waf:ListSqlInjectionMatchSets.Title: ListSqlInjectionMatchSets

waf:ListWebACLs.Description: Returns an array of WebACLSummary objects in the response.
waf:ListWebACLs.Title: ListWebACLs

waf:ListXssMatchSets.Description: Returns an array of XssMatchSet objects.
waf:ListXssMatchSets.Title: ListXssMatchSets

waf:UpdateByteMatchSet.Description: Inserts or deletes ByteMatchTuple objects (filters) in a ByteMatchSet. For each ByteMatchTuple object, you specify the following values:
waf:UpdateByteMatchSet.Title: UpdateByteMatchSet

waf:UpdateIPSet.Description: Inserts or deletes IPSetDescriptor objects in an IPSet. For each IPSetDescriptor object, you specify the following values:
waf:UpdateIPSet.Title: UpdateIPSet

waf:UpdateRateBasedRule.Description: Inserts or deletes Predicate objects in a rule and updates the RateLimit in the rule.
waf:UpdateRateBasedRule.Title: UpdateRateBasedRule

waf:UpdateRule.Description: Inserts or deletes Predicate objects in a Rule. Each Predicate object identifies a predicate, such as a ByteMatchSet or an IPSet, that specifies the web requests that you want to allow, block, or count. If you add more than one predicate to a Rule, a request must match all of the specifications to be allowed, blocked, or counted. For example, suppose you add the following to a Rule:
waf:UpdateRule.Title: UpdateRule

waf:UpdateSizeConstraintSet.Description: Inserts or deletes SizeConstraint objects (filters) in a SizeConstraintSet. For each SizeConstraint object, you specify the following values:
waf:UpdateSizeConstraintSet.Title: UpdateSizeConstraintSet

waf:UpdateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Inserts or deletes SqlInjectionMatchTuple objects (filters) in a SqlInjectionMatchSet. For each SqlInjectionMatchTuple object, you specify the following values:
waf:UpdateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: UpdateSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf:UpdateWebACL.Description: Inserts or deletes ActivatedRule objects in a WebACL. Each Rule identifies web requests that you want to allow, block, or count. When you update a WebACL, you specify the following values:
waf:UpdateWebACL.Title: UpdateWebACL

waf:UpdateXssMatchSet.Description: Inserts or deletes XssMatchTuple objects (filters) in an XssMatchSet. For each XssMatchTuple object, you specify the following values:
waf:UpdateXssMatchSet.Title: UpdateXssMatchSet

waf-regional:AssociateWebACL.Description: Associates a web ACL with a resource.
waf-regional:AssociateWebACL.Title: AssociateWebACL

waf-regional:CreateByteMatchSet.Description: Creates a ByteMatchSet. You then use UpdateByteMatchSet to identify the part of a web request that you want AWS WAF to inspect, such as the values of the User-Agent header or the query string. For example, you can create a ByteMatchSet that matches any requests with User-Agent headers that contain the string BadBot. You can then configure AWS WAF to reject those requests.
waf-regional:CreateByteMatchSet.Title: CreateByteMatchSet

waf-regional:CreateIPSet.Description: Creates an IPSet, which you use to specify which web requests you want to allow or block based on the IP addresses that the requests originate from. For example, if you're receiving a lot of requests from one or more individual IP addresses or one or more ranges of IP addresses and you want to block the requests, you can create an IPSet that contains those IP addresses and then configure AWS WAF to block the requests.
waf-regional:CreateIPSet.Title: CreateIPSet

waf-regional:CreateRateBasedRule.Description: Creates a RateBasedRule. The RateBasedRule contains a RateLimit, which specifies the maximum number of requests that AWS WAF allows from a specified IP address in a five-minute period. The RateBasedRule also contains the IPSet objects, ByteMatchSet objects, and other predicates that identify the requests that you want to count or block if these requests exceed the RateLimit.
waf-regional:CreateRateBasedRule.Title: CreateRateBasedRule

waf-regional:CreateRule.Description: Creates a Rule, which contains the IPSet objects, ByteMatchSet objects, and other predicates that identify the requests that you want to block. If you add more than one predicate to a Rule, a request must match all of the specifications to be allowed or blocked. For example, suppose you add the following to a Rule:
waf-regional:CreateRule.Title: CreateRule

waf-regional:CreateSizeConstraintSet.Description: Creates a SizeConstraintSet. You then use UpdateSizeConstraintSet to identify the part of a web request that you want AWS WAF to check for length, such as the length of the User-Agent header or the length of the query string. For example, you can create a SizeConstraintSet that matches any requests that have a query string that is longer than 100 bytes. You can then configure AWS WAF to reject those requests.
waf-regional:CreateSizeConstraintSet.Title: CreateSizeConstraintSet

waf-regional:CreateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Creates a SqlInjectionMatchSet, which you use to allow, block, or count requests that contain snippets of SQL code in a specified part of web requests. AWS WAF searches for character sequences that are likely to be malicious strings.
waf-regional:CreateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: CreateSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf-regional:CreateWebACL.Description: Creates a WebACL, which contains the Rules that identify the CloudFront web requests that you want to allow, block, or count. AWS WAF evaluates Rules in order based on the value of Priority for each Rule.
waf-regional:CreateWebACL.Title: CreateWebACL

waf-regional:CreateXssMatchSet.Description: Creates an XssMatchSet, which you use to allow, block, or count requests that contain cross-site scripting attacks in the specified part of web requests. AWS WAF searches for character sequences that are likely to be malicious strings.
waf-regional:CreateXssMatchSet.Title: CreateXssMatchSet

waf-regional:DeleteByteMatchSet.Description: Permanently deletes a ByteMatchSet. You can't delete a ByteMatchSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still includes any ByteMatchTuple objects (any filters).
waf-regional:DeleteByteMatchSet.Title: DeleteByteMatchSet

waf-regional:DeleteIPSet.Description: Permanently deletes an IPSet. You can't delete an IPSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still includes any IP addresses.
waf-regional:DeleteIPSet.Title: DeleteIPSet

waf-regional:DeleteRateBasedRule.Description: Permanently deletes a RateBasedRule. You can't delete a rule if it's still used in any WebACL objects or if it still includes any predicates, such as ByteMatchSet objects.
waf-regional:DeleteRateBasedRule.Title: DeleteRateBasedRule

waf-regional:DeleteRule.Description: Permanently deletes a Rule. You can't delete a Rule if it's still used in any WebACL objects or if it still includes any predicates, such as ByteMatchSet objects.
waf-regional:DeleteRule.Title: DeleteRule

waf-regional:DeleteSizeConstraintSet.Description: Permanently deletes a SizeConstraintSet. You can't delete a SizeConstraintSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still includes any SizeConstraint objects (any filters).
waf-regional:DeleteSizeConstraintSet.Title: DeleteSizeConstraintSet

waf-regional:DeleteSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Permanently deletes a SqlInjectionMatchSet. You can't delete a SqlInjectionMatchSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still contains any SqlInjectionMatchTuple objects.
waf-regional:DeleteSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: DeleteSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf-regional:DeleteWebACL.Description: Permanently deletes a WebACL. You can't delete a WebACL if it still contains any Rules.
waf-regional:DeleteWebACL.Title: DeleteWebACL

waf-regional:DeleteXssMatchSet.Description: Permanently deletes an XssMatchSet. You can't delete an XssMatchSet if it's still used in any Rules or if it still contains any XssMatchTuple objects.
waf-regional:DeleteXssMatchSet.Title: DeleteXssMatchSet

waf-regional:DisassociateWebACL.Description: Removes a web ACL from the specified resource.
waf-regional:DisassociateWebACL.Title: DisassociateWebACL

waf-regional:GetByteMatchSet.Description: Returns the ByteMatchSet specified by ByteMatchSetId.
waf-regional:GetByteMatchSet.Title: GetByteMatchSet

waf-regional:GetChangeToken.Description: When you want to create, update, or delete AWS WAF objects, get a change token and include the change token in the create, update, or delete request. Change tokens ensure that your application doesn't submit conflicting requests to AWS WAF.
waf-regional:GetChangeToken.Title: GetChangeToken

waf-regional:GetChangeTokenStatus.Description: Returns the status of a ChangeToken that you got by calling GetChangeToken. ChangeTokenStatus is one of the following values:
waf-regional:GetChangeTokenStatus.Title: GetChangeTokenStatus

waf-regional:GetIPSet.Description: Returns the IPSet that is specified by IPSetId.
waf-regional:GetIPSet.Title: GetIPSet

waf-regional:GetRateBasedRule.Description: Returns the RateBasedRule that is specified by the RuleId that you included in the GetRateBasedRule request.
waf-regional:GetRateBasedRule.Title: GetRateBasedRule

waf-regional:GetRateBasedRuleManagedKeys.Description: Returns an array of IP addresses currently being blocked by the RateBasedRule that is specified by the RuleId. The maximum number of managed keys that will be blocked is 10,000. If more than 10,000 addresses exceed the rate limit, the 10,000 addresses with the highest rates will be blocked.
waf-regional:GetRateBasedRuleManagedKeys.Title: GetRateBasedRuleManagedKeys

waf-regional:GetRule.Description: Returns the Rule that is specified by the RuleId that you included in the GetRule request.
waf-regional:GetRule.Title: GetRule

waf-regional:GetSampledRequests.Description: Gets detailed information about a specified number of requests--a sample--that AWS WAF randomly selects from among the first 5,000 requests that your AWS resource received during a time range that you choose. You can specify a sample size of up to 500 requests, and you can specify any time range in the previous three hours.
waf-regional:GetSampledRequests.Title: GetSampledRequests

waf-regional:GetSizeConstraintSet.Description: Returns the SizeConstraintSet specified by SizeConstraintSetId.
waf-regional:GetSizeConstraintSet.Title: GetSizeConstraintSet

waf-regional:GetSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Returns the SqlInjectionMatchSet that is specified by SqlInjectionMatchSetId.
waf-regional:GetSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: GetSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf-regional:GetWebACL.Description: Returns the WebACL that is specified by WebACLId.
waf-regional:GetWebACL.Title: GetWebACL

waf-regional:GetWebACLForResource.Description: Returns the web ACL for the specified resource.
waf-regional:GetWebACLForResource.Title: GetWebACLForResource

waf-regional:GetXssMatchSet.Description: Returns the XssMatchSet that is specified by XssMatchSetId.
waf-regional:GetXssMatchSet.Title: GetXssMatchSet

waf-regional:ListByteMatchSets.Description: Returns an array of ByteMatchSetSummary objects.
waf-regional:ListByteMatchSets.Title: ListByteMatchSets

waf-regional:ListIPSets.Description: Returns an array of IPSetSummary objects in the response.
waf-regional:ListIPSets.Title: ListIPSets

waf-regional:ListResourcesForWebACL.Description: Returns an array of resources associated with the specified web ACL.
waf-regional:ListResourcesForWebACL.Title: ListResourcesForWebACL

waf-regional:ListRules.Description: Returns an array of RuleSummary objects.
waf-regional:ListRules.Title: ListRules

waf-regional:ListSizeConstraintSets.Description: Returns an array of SizeConstraintSetSummary objects.
waf-regional:ListSizeConstraintSets.Title: ListSizeConstraintSets

waf-regional:ListSqlInjectionMatchSets.Description: Returns an array of SqlInjectionMatchSet objects.
waf-regional:ListSqlInjectionMatchSets.Title: ListSqlInjectionMatchSets

waf-regional:ListWebACLs.Description: Returns an array of WebACLSummary objects in the response.
waf-regional:ListWebACLs.Title: ListWebACLs

waf-regional:ListXssMatchSets.Description: Returns an array of XssMatchSet objects.
waf-regional:ListXssMatchSets.Title: ListXssMatchSets

waf-regional:UpdateByteMatchSet.Title: UpdateByteMatchSet

waf-regional:UpdateIPSet.Description: Inserts or deletes IPSetDescriptor objects in an IPSet. For each IPSetDescriptor object, you specify the following values:
waf-regional:UpdateIPSet.Title: UpdateIPSet

waf-regional:UpdateRateBasedRule.Description: Inserts or deletes Predicate objects in a rule and updates the RateLimit in the rule.
waf-regional:UpdateRateBasedRule.Title: UpdateRateBasedRule

waf-regional:UpdateRule.Description: Inserts or deletes Predicate objects in a Rule. Each Predicate object identifies a predicate, such as a ByteMatchSet or an IPSet, that specifies the web requests that you want to allow, block, or count. If you add more than one predicate to a Rule, a request must match all of the specifications to be allowed, blocked, or counted. For example, suppose you add the following to a Rule:
waf-regional:UpdateRule.Title: UpdateRule

waf-regional:UpdateSizeConstraintSet.Description: Inserts or deletes SizeConstraint objects (filters) in a SizeConstraintSet. For each SizeConstraint object, you specify the following values:
waf-regional:UpdateSizeConstraintSet.Title: UpdateSizeConstraintSet

waf-regional:UpdateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Description: Inserts or deletes SqlInjectionMatchTuple objects (filters) in a SqlInjectionMatchSet. For each SqlInjectionMatchTuple object, you specify the following values:
waf-regional:UpdateSqlInjectionMatchSet.Title: UpdateSqlInjectionMatchSet

waf-regional:UpdateWebACL.Description: Inserts or deletes ActivatedRule objects in a WebACL. Each Rule identifies web requests that you want to allow, block, or count. When you update a WebACL, you specify the following values:
waf-regional:UpdateWebACL.Title: UpdateWebACL

waf-regional:UpdateXssMatchSet.Description: Inserts or deletes XssMatchTuple objects (filters) in an XssMatchSet. For each XssMatchTuple object, you specify the following values:
waf-regional:UpdateXssMatchSet.Title: UpdateXssMatchSet

workspaces:DescribeWorkspaceBundles.Description: Obtains information about the WorkSpace bundles that are available to your account in the specified region.
workspaces:DescribeWorkspaceBundles.Title: DescribeWorkspaceBundles

workspaces:DescribeWorkspaceDirectories.Description: Retrieves information about the AWS Directory Service directories in the region that are registered with Amazon WorkSpaces and are available to your account.
workspaces:DescribeWorkspaceDirectories.Title: DescribeWorkspaceDirectories

workspaces:DescribeWorkspaces.Description: Obtains information about the specified WorkSpaces.
workspaces:DescribeWorkspaces.Title: DescribeWorkspaces

workspaces:DescribeWorkspacesConnectionS.Description: Describes the connection status of a specified WorkSpace.
workspaces:DescribeWorkspacesConnectionS.Title: DescribeWorkspacesConnectionStatus

workspaces:ModifyWorkspaceProperties.Description: Modifies the WorkSpace properties, including the running mode and AutoStop time.
workspaces:ModifyWorkspaceProperties.Title: ModifyWorkspaceProperties

workspaces:StartWorkspaces.Description: Starts the specified WorkSpaces. The WorkSpaces must have a running mode of AutoStop and a state of STOPPED.
workspaces:StartWorkspaces.Title: StartWorkspaces

workspaces:StopWorkspaces.Description: Stops the specified WorkSpaces. The WorkSpaces must have a running mode of AutoStop and a state of AVAILABLE, IMPAIRED, UNHEALTHY, or ERROR.
workspaces:StopWorkspaces.Title: StopWorkspaces

xray:BatchGetTraces.Description: Retrieves a list of traces specified by ID. Each trace is a collection of segment documents that originates from a single request. Use GetTraceSummaries to get a list of trace IDs.
xray:BatchGetTraces.Title: BatchGetTraces

xray:GetServiceGraph.Description: Retrieves a document that describes services that process incoming requests, and downstream services that they call as a result. Root services process incoming requests and make calls to downstream services. Root services are applications that use the AWS X-Ray SDK. Downstream services can be other applications, AWS resources, HTTP web APIs, or SQL databases.
xray:GetServiceGraph.Title: GetServiceGraph

xray:GetTraceGraph.Description: Retrieves a service graph for one or more specific trace IDs.
xray:GetTraceGraph.Title: GetTraceGraph

xray:GetTraceSummaries.Description: Retrieves IDs and metadata for traces available for a specified time frame using an optional filter. To get the full traces, pass the trace IDs to BatchGetTraces.
xray:GetTraceSummaries.Title: GetTraceSummaries

xray:PutTelemetryRecords.Description: Used by the AWS X-Ray daemon to upload telemetry.
xray:PutTelemetryRecords.Title: PutTelemetryRecords

xray:PutTraceSegments.Description: Uploads segment documents to AWS X-Ray. The X-Ray SDK generates segment documents and sends them to the X-Ray daemon, which uploads them in batches. A segment document can be a completed segment, an in-progress segment, or an array of subsegments.
xray:PutTraceSegments.Title: PutTraceSegments
